1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:02,879
So you think that money is the root of all evil?

2
00:00:02,879 --> 00:00:05,200
Have you ever asked what is the root of money?

3
00:00:05,200 --> 00:00:10,880
With those words, Francisco Danconea, a man everyone believes is a worthless playboy,

4
00:00:10,880 --> 00:00:16,239
drops his mask and delivers one of the most important philosophical arguments in literature.

5
00:00:16,239 --> 00:00:19,600
This is the money speech, and it changes everything.

6
00:00:20,100 --> 00:00:24,739
Previously, Francisco Donconia, once the greatest industrialist of his generation,

7
00:00:24,739 --> 00:00:29,300
now squanders his fortune on scandals. His copper mines produce less each year.

8
00:00:29,300 --> 00:00:32,340
He seems to be deliberately destroying everything he built.

9
00:00:32,340 --> 00:00:34,820
Why would a man of such ability choose destruction?

10
00:00:35,780 --> 00:00:37,539
What does he know that we don't?

11
00:00:38,579 --> 00:00:40,179
Welcome back to Atlas Shrugged.

12
00:00:41,140 --> 00:00:45,939
In our last episode, we explored the prime movers, the industrialists and creators who

13
00:00:45,939 --> 00:00:51,299
keep the world running despite growing opposition. Today, we're diving into Chapter 5,

14
00:00:52,020 --> 00:00:58,100
the climax of the Danconias. This chapter contains one of the most famous passages in the entire novel,

15
00:00:58,820 --> 00:01:04,900
Francisco Donconia's Money Speech. By the end of this episode, you'll understand why Francisco

16
00:01:04,900 --> 00:01:11,700
argues that money is a tool of virtue, not evil. You'll see how the intellectuals at the party

17
00:01:11,700 --> 00:01:16,819
provide cover for looters. You'll witness the first real meeting between Rairden and Francisco.

18
00:01:17,540 --> 00:01:22,819
And you'll understand why this chapter marks a turning point in the novel. Let's dive in.

19
00:01:23,319 --> 00:01:27,819
The chapter centers on a party at the Reardon home, hosted by Lillian Reardon.

20
00:01:27,819 --> 00:01:33,719
This gathering brings together the novel's main characters in a social setting that exposes the conflicts between them.

21
00:01:33,719 --> 00:01:39,819
At this party, intellectuals like Dr. Pritchett and Balfe Ubank spout nihilistic philosophy,

22
00:01:39,819 --> 00:01:43,420
while businessmen like James Taggart scheme in corners.

23
00:01:43,420 --> 00:01:49,319
The cultural establishment is on full display, people who live off the wealth created by producers,

24
00:01:49,319 --> 00:01:52,420
while despising the very active production.

25
00:01:52,519 --> 00:01:55,019
Here's what makes this scene so powerful.

26
00:01:55,019 --> 00:01:59,519
The intellectuals proclaim that man is worthless, that reason is a superstition,

27
00:01:59,519 --> 00:02:02,519
and that suffering is the essence of life.

28
00:02:02,519 --> 00:02:10,520
Meanwhile, they enjoy champagne, find food, and all the products of the industrial civilization they claim to despise.

29
00:02:10,520 --> 00:02:16,919
The party represents the cultural establishment that provides intellectual cover for the looters assault on the producers,

30
00:02:16,919 --> 00:02:22,020
and it's into this environment that Francisco Danconea drops his philosophical bomb.

31
00:02:22,520 --> 00:02:25,560
When someone at the party makes a casual comment that,

32
00:02:25,560 --> 00:02:27,800
money is the root of all evil.

33
00:02:27,800 --> 00:02:31,560
Francisco, who has been playing the role of idle playboy,

34
00:02:31,560 --> 00:02:33,479
suddenly drops his mask.

35
00:02:33,479 --> 00:02:34,919
He responds,

36
00:02:34,919 --> 00:02:37,719
so you think that money is the root of all evil?

37
00:02:37,719 --> 00:02:40,680
Have you ever asked what is the root of money?

38
00:02:40,680 --> 00:02:44,680
What follows is a detailed philosophical defense of money.

39
00:02:44,680 --> 00:02:48,039
This speech is one of the novel's most important passages,

40
00:02:48,039 --> 00:02:51,479
presenting RAN's view of money as a symbol of human achievement

41
00:02:51,479 --> 00:02:53,159
and free exchange.

42
00:02:53,159 --> 00:02:55,960
Francisco's first point,

43
00:02:55,960 --> 00:02:58,840
money is a tool of exchange,

44
00:02:58,840 --> 00:03:01,479
which can't exist unless there are goods produced

45
00:03:01,479 --> 00:03:04,039
and men able to produce them.

46
00:03:04,039 --> 00:03:06,840
Money doesn't create wealth.

47
00:03:06,840 --> 00:03:09,400
It represents wealth that has already been created

48
00:03:09,400 --> 00:03:11,159
through productive effort.

49
00:03:11,159 --> 00:03:13,639
His second point,

50
00:03:13,639 --> 00:03:16,039
money is made

51
00:03:16,039 --> 00:03:18,680
before it can be looted or mooched,

52
00:03:18,680 --> 00:03:21,560
made by the effort of every honest man,

53
00:03:21,560 --> 00:03:23,879
each to the extent of his ability.

54
00:03:23,879 --> 00:03:27,560
An honest man is one who knows that he can't consume more

55
00:03:27,560 --> 00:03:29,319
than he has produced.

56
00:03:29,319 --> 00:03:31,960
His third point,

57
00:03:31,960 --> 00:03:35,800
money is the barometer of a society's virtue.

58
00:03:35,800 --> 00:03:39,560
When money ceases to be the tool by which men deal with one another,

59
00:03:39,560 --> 00:03:44,120
then men become the tools of men.

60
00:03:44,120 --> 00:03:46,759
This is the core of Francisco's argument,

61
00:03:46,759 --> 00:03:50,039
if not money, then force.

62
00:03:50,039 --> 00:03:51,639
Here's an important note.

63
00:03:51,639 --> 00:03:55,159
Francisco argues that if money is not the medium of exchange,

64
00:03:55,159 --> 00:03:56,919
then force must be.

65
00:03:56,919 --> 00:04:00,599
Men will have to obtain goods by seizing them from others.

66
00:04:00,599 --> 00:04:02,919
Money represents voluntary trade.

67
00:04:02,919 --> 00:04:05,639
Its abolition means the rule of force.

68
00:04:05,639 --> 00:04:08,039
Let me read you some of the key passages.

69
00:04:08,039 --> 00:04:10,280
Money is the material shape of the principle

70
00:04:10,280 --> 00:04:12,199
that men who wish to deal with one another

71
00:04:12,199 --> 00:04:15,719
must deal by trade and give value for value.

72
00:04:15,719 --> 00:04:19,639
Run for your life from any man who tells you that money is evil.

73
00:04:19,639 --> 00:04:23,639
That sentence is the leper's bell of an approaching looter.

74
00:04:23,639 --> 00:04:27,079
When you see that trading is done, not by consent,

75
00:04:27,079 --> 00:04:29,000
but by compulsion.

76
00:04:29,000 --> 00:04:31,079
When you see that in order to produce,

77
00:04:31,079 --> 00:04:35,800
you need to obtain permission from men who produce nothing.

78
00:04:35,800 --> 00:04:39,639
You may know that your society is doomed.

79
00:04:39,639 --> 00:04:41,800
The core argument is this.

80
00:04:41,800 --> 00:04:44,839
Francisco argues that money is a tool that allows people

81
00:04:44,839 --> 00:04:47,000
to trade value for value.

82
00:04:47,000 --> 00:04:48,680
When people condemn money,

83
00:04:48,680 --> 00:04:50,839
they're really condemning the freedom to trade,

84
00:04:50,839 --> 00:04:53,399
and advocating for a system where goods are distributed

85
00:04:53,399 --> 00:04:55,879
by force rather than by voluntary exchange.

86
00:04:56,379 --> 00:05:02,220
Now let's look at the intellectuals at the party, the people who provide philosophical cover for the looters.

87
00:05:02,220 --> 00:05:13,819
First, there's Dr. Simon Pritchett, a philosophy professor who preaches that reason is a superstition that nothing can be known, and that man's purpose is to be tractable.

88
00:05:13,819 --> 00:05:17,139
He supports the equalization of opportunity bill.

89
00:05:17,139 --> 00:05:23,420
Then there's Balfe Ubank, a literary leader, who believes suffering is the essence of life.

90
00:05:23,420 --> 00:05:29,579
He wants a law limiting book sales to 10,000 copies, to force people to read better literature.

91
00:05:29,579 --> 00:05:31,420
Notice the contradiction.

92
00:05:31,420 --> 00:05:34,300
He wants government force to promote his values.

93
00:05:34,300 --> 00:05:40,220
Mort Liddy is a composer who writes old-fashioned scores for money and modern atonal music for prestige.

94
00:05:40,220 --> 00:05:43,579
He embodies the split between values and pretensions.

95
00:05:43,579 --> 00:05:47,259
He knows what's good but pretends otherwise for social acceptance.

96
00:05:47,259 --> 00:05:51,579
Finally, there's Bertram Scutter, editor of the Future magazine,

97
00:05:51,660 --> 00:05:54,860
who wrote an article calling Reardon the Octopus.

98
00:05:54,860 --> 00:06:00,860
He represents the media's hostility to business, attacking the producers while living off their creations.

99
00:06:00,860 --> 00:06:03,740
These intellectuals share something in common.

100
00:06:03,740 --> 00:06:11,579
They preach nihilism and anti-reason philosophy while enjoying all the benefits of rational, productive civilization.

101
00:06:11,579 --> 00:06:14,779
Their ideas provide the moral cover that makes looting possible.

102
00:06:15,279 --> 00:06:19,600
At the party, Hank Reardon and Francisco D'anconia have their first real conversation.

103
00:06:20,160 --> 00:06:24,480
Despite being told that Francisco is his enemy, Reardon finds himself intrigued by the man's

104
00:06:24,480 --> 00:06:30,959
unusual honesty and insight. Francisco says, Mr. Reardon, I came to this party solely in order to

105
00:06:30,959 --> 00:06:36,639
meet you. My motives cannot interest you at present. I want to learn to understand you.

106
00:06:37,519 --> 00:06:42,000
Francisco's directness contrasts sharply with the evasiveness of everyone else at the party.

107
00:06:42,480 --> 00:06:47,360
Reardon senses that Francisco is unlike anyone he has ever met. Then comes the mysterious

108
00:06:47,360 --> 00:06:52,560
statement. Francisco tells Reardon that he wants to understand him, and hints that he eventually

109
00:06:52,560 --> 00:06:59,040
wants Reardon to lose money. Why would someone who clearly admires Reardon want him to lose money?

110
00:07:00,240 --> 00:07:05,759
This question will drive much of the novel's plot. Francisco understands something that Reardon

111
00:07:05,759 --> 00:07:13,120
doesn't yet see, and by the end of the book, we'll understand it too.

112
00:07:13,620 --> 00:07:16,980
Let's synthesize the key themes developed in this chapter.

113
00:07:16,980 --> 00:07:19,860
First, money as virtue.

114
00:07:19,860 --> 00:07:24,339
Francisco's speech presents money as a tool of achievement and free exchange.

115
00:07:24,339 --> 00:07:28,660
Hostility to money is hostility to human accomplishment itself.

116
00:07:28,660 --> 00:07:31,860
Second, intellectual corruption.

117
00:07:31,860 --> 00:07:34,980
The intellectuals at the party provide philosophical cover for

118
00:07:34,980 --> 00:07:37,620
looting by preaching that nothing can be known.

119
00:07:37,620 --> 00:07:41,540
Man is worthless, and suffering is noble.

120
00:07:41,620 --> 00:07:44,579
Third, social masks.

121
00:07:44,579 --> 00:07:50,019
The party reveals the gap between people's social poses and their true values.

122
00:07:50,019 --> 00:07:54,500
Francisco drops his playboy mask to reveal unexpected depth.

123
00:07:54,500 --> 00:07:57,300
Fourth, recognition.

124
00:07:57,300 --> 00:08:01,139
Reardon and Dagnie recognize each other as kindred spirits,

125
00:08:01,139 --> 00:08:03,860
different from everyone else at the gathering.

126
00:08:03,860 --> 00:08:06,500
They sense something important about each other,

127
00:08:06,500 --> 00:08:09,699
even before they fully understand it.

128
00:08:09,699 --> 00:08:11,379
Be careful here.

129
00:08:11,379 --> 00:08:14,259
At the party, Dagnie notices Lily and wearing the

130
00:08:14,259 --> 00:08:18,740
Reardon Metal bracelet and wearing it as a symbol of contempt.

131
00:08:18,740 --> 00:08:22,019
In a later scene, Dagnie will exchange one of her own valuable

132
00:08:22,019 --> 00:08:25,459
jewels for the bracelet, recognizing its true worth.

133
00:08:25,459 --> 00:08:27,459
This detail matters.

134
00:08:27,959 --> 00:08:30,360
Let's recap what we learned today.

135
00:08:30,360 --> 00:08:34,840
Francisco's money speech presents money as a tool of achievement and free exchange,

136
00:08:34,840 --> 00:08:36,600
not as a source of evil.

137
00:08:36,600 --> 00:08:40,600
The party intellectuals preach nihilism and anti-reason philosophy,

138
00:08:40,600 --> 00:08:43,240
providing cover for the looters assault on producers.

139
00:08:44,279 --> 00:08:48,679
Ray Arden and Francisco meet for the first time,

140
00:08:49,639 --> 00:08:52,679
beginning a relationship that will prove central to the novel.

141
00:08:53,399 --> 00:08:57,799
The social gathering exposes the conflict between producers who create value

142
00:08:57,799 --> 00:09:01,159
and parasites who consume it while despising its source.

143
00:09:01,879 --> 00:09:07,720
And Francisco drops his mask briefly, revealing that he is far more than the idol playboy he pretends to be.

